Oh? A book... Cleave grins with anticipation as he pulls out his deck, giving it one last look-over before the big game.
His NetNavi, SmithMan, chimes in. Despite my insistence otherwise, you continue to participate in this childs game..." SmithMan sighs. It is too late to quit now. If you truly intend to become champion of this tournament, then there shall be no restraint! Show no mercy to your opponent!
Cleave merely grins in response, the light gleaming off of his glasses as he deftly sifts through his cards. Oh, dont worry, SmithMan, he assures him. I dont intend to lose.
Cleave confidently sets foot onto the battlefield - the poorly-lit back room of the GatchaLand arcade, plastic white foldable table taking center stage. He takes his seat in an old, rusting folding chair that squeaks and complains at the slightest hint of pressure, one of its legs not quite touching the floor. Across from cleave, his opponent takes their seat - a slightly pudgy 10 year old boy named Patrick, absentmindedly sucking on a lollipop in his mouth. A small group of children behind him cheer him on. Presumably, the boys friends.
The arcade owner, a boisterous man known as Chance, slams his hand on the end of the table. Alright, boys and girls! Welcome to the championship round of the GatchaLand Local Super Fighting Cards Tournament. Please cut one anothers decks!
Cleave pushes up his glasses and offers his deck for the boy to cut. The names Cleave, he sleazily remarks. Lets see if youre as good as they say, eh? He flashes the boy an offputting grin. The boy stares at Cleave with a hesitation and mistrust. He doesnt reply, but takes Cleaves deck and cuts it as Cleave does the same to the boys deck.
Players, set up your decks! Chance interjects, after they had both cut one anothers cards. Each player sets their cards on the table, and the game is ready to begin.
You have no idea what youre in for, kid. Im gonna introduce you to a whole new world of losing! Cleave thinks to himself as he draws his opening hand. But he takes one look at his cards, and his mood instantly sours. What-!? He exclaims in surprise. Hes quick to perform damage control, readjusting his glasses after nearly knocking them off his face. ...Heh, I mean, what could you possibly do against this unbeatable strategy? SmithMan chimes in through an earpiece in Cleaves ear. It appears your most powerful assets remain in your deck. Remain calm and bide for time.
And now to determine who will play first! Chance flips a plastic coin, which clatters onto the table. Cleave would be playing second. He feels his heart sink a little lower.
Play goes on for just a few short turns. Every time Cleave thinks hes drawn a key to victory, his shockingly adept opponent has an answer. At every twist and turn, Cleave is humiliated. When the dust settles, Cleave is the loser.
And the winner is...! Chance walks over to Patrick and raises his hand. His crowd of friends cheers. I-Impossible...! Cleave drops the cards in his hand onto the table in disbelief. I cant believe this... Bested by a child! SmithMan chimes in. I warned you, it would only be natural that a child excels at a childs game.
Cleave stands straight up and points his finger accusingly at the child. You, my worthy adversary, have made a grave enemy. You will rue the day you crossed Cleave Ayasugi! I may have been bested on this day, but I will return with a vengeance! Sleep with one eye open, Patrick! Your day of reckoning soon approaches! He spins around and dramatically walks out of the room, leaving his cards on the table. Everyone watches blankly as he tries to pull on the push door.
What a weirdo, one of Patricks friends comments.
